sentations of the German-Czech Conflict in Texts by Peter Härtling, Pavel Kohout, and Jörg Bernig -- tAcknowledging Each Other as Victims: An Unmet Challenge in the Process of Polish-German Reconciliation -- tAttempts at (Re)Conciliation: Polish-German Relations in Literary Texts by Stefan Chwin, Pawel Huelle, and Olga Tokarczuk -- tHistorical Consciousness and the German Present -- tThe Collateral Damage of Enlightenment: How Grandchildren Understand the History of National Socialist Crimes and Their Grandfathers’ Past -- tThe Haunted Screen (Again): The Historical Unconscious of Contemporary German Thrillers -- tRape, War, and Outrage: Changing Perceptions on German Victimhood in the Period of Post-unification -- tComing to Terms with Vergangenheitsbewältigung. Walser’s Sonntagsrede, the Kosovo War, and the Transformation of German Historical Consciousness -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex of Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume examines the politics of history and memory in Germany today through a review and analysis of seminal developments in the current discourse on 1933 – 1945. An interdisplicinary work, this book examines questions of representing the past from the perspective of literary studies, social psychology, film studies, history, and cultural studies.Themes include transgenerational memory and remembrance, the air war and German literature, commemoration and silences, transnational reconciliation, and historical consciousness in the German present. The collected essays make clear that as the current discourse contributes toward an historically informed, differentiated understanding of individuals’ roles in the Third Reich and World War Two, victim and perpetrator identities cannot be defined as exclusive from one another. The discourse emphasizes personal over collective experience and answers questions of responsibility and guilt on the individual level.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aConflict of generationszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xMoral and ethical aspects. 0aMemoryxPolitical aspectszGermany. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xHistoriography. 4aErinnerung. 4aGeschichtsbewusstsein. 4aSchuld. 4aWeltkrieg II /i. d. Literatur. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aGuilt.  aWW II (in literature).  ahistorical awareness.  amemory.1 aASSMANN, ALEIDA, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBECKER, DANIEL, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCOHEN-PFISTER, LAUREL, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen-Pfister, Laurel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFOX, THOMAS C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGLAJAR, VALENTINA, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHAGE, VOLKER, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHALVERSON, RACHEL, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLUTOMSKI, PAWEL, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMARTIN, JAMES, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPRAGER, BRAD, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSATHE, NIKHIL, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSEGELCKE, ELKE, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSINKA, MARGIT, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVEES-GULANI, SUSANNE, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWELZER, HARALD, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWIENRO